import os

# Define the parent directory
parent_dir = 'autonomous_driving'

# Define the child directories to create
dirs = [
    f'{parent_dir}/data/images',
    f'{parent_dir}/data/labels',
    f'{parent_dir}/models',
    f'{parent_dir}/outputs',
    f'{parent_dir}/notebooks'
]

# Create the directories
for d in dirs:
    os.makedirs(d, exist_ok=True)

print("Directory structure created successfully.")

#Cleaning data and keeping relavent columns
import pandas as pd

csv_path = '/content/autonomous_driving/data/Tesla - Deaths.csv'
df = pd.read_csv(csv_path, engine='python', on_bad_lines='warn')

# Columns to keep (with whitespace cleaned up)
columns_to_keep = [
    'Year', 'Date', 'Country', 'State', 'Description', 'Deaths',
    'Tesla driver', 'Tesla occupant', 'Other vehicle', 'Cyclists/ Peds',
    'Model', 'Autopilot claimed', 'Verified Tesla Autopilot Deaths',
    'Verified Tesla Autopilot Deaths + All Deaths Reported to NHTSA SGO',
    'Source', 'Deceased 1'
]

# Clean column names to remove whitespace
df.columns = [col.strip() for col in df.columns]
columns_to_keep = [col.strip() for col in columns_to_keep]

# Filter DataFrame to keep only the selected columns
df_clean = df[columns_to_keep]

# Drop duplicates
df_clean = df_clean.drop_duplicates()

# Drop rows missing essential fields (Date, Description, Deaths)
df_clean = df_clean.dropna(subset=['Date', 'Description', 'Deaths'])

print("Cleaned DataFrame shape:", df_clean.shape)
print("Columns now:", df_clean.columns.tolist())
print(df_clean.head())

# Save to CSV (optional)
df_clean.to_csv('/content/autonomous_driving/data/Tesla-Deaths_cleaned.csv', index=False)
print("Cleaned CSV saved as Tesla-Deaths_cleaned.csv!")

# -- 1. Imports and Data Loading --
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load your cleaned data
df = pd.read_csv('/content/autonomous_driving/data/Tesla-Deaths_cleaned.csv')
df.columns = [col.strip() for col in df.columns]  # Clean column names

# -- 2. Data Cleaning: Make "count" columns numeric --
count_columns = [
    'Tesla driver', 'Tesla occupant', 'Other vehicle', 'Cyclists/ Peds', 'Deaths'
]
for col in count_columns:
    if col in df.columns:
        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col].replace(['-', ' '], 0), errors='coerce').fillna(0).astype(int)

# Ensure date is parsed correctly, add Year/Day columns
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'], errors='coerce')
df['Year'] = df['Date'].dt.year
df['DayOfWeek'] = df['Date'].dt.day_name()

# 8. Proportion: Tesla Occupant Deaths

# Tesla driver and Tesla occupant are both relevant.
has_occupant_death = (df['Tesla driver'] > 0) | (df['Tesla occupant'] > 0)
prop_occupant_death = has_occupant_death.mean()

1. Preliminary Data Inspection and Cleaning¶

a. Data Types, Missing Values, Duplicates¶

Columns were inspected for data type consistency.

Several columns had string entries such as "-", which were converted to zeros or NaN for analysis.

No major duplicate rows were found.

Some columns had missing or non-informative values (e.g., Unnamed columns).

b. Remove Irrelevant Columns¶

Non-essential columns (e.g., redundant URLs, Unnamed columns, individual deceased names) were dropped.

Core columns retained: date, country, state, description, deaths, Tesla driver, Tesla occupant, other vehicle, cyclists/peds, model, and autopilot-related flags.

2. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

a. Events by Date, Year, Day, State, Country¶

Events occurred across multiple years, with a trend of increase in recent years.

California leads by a wide margin in state-level events.

US overwhelmingly dominates country-level events; few in Canada, Europe, Asia.

Events are distributed throughout the week, with a slight concentration on weekends.

b. Aspects of Death Events¶

Number of Victims (Deaths) in Each Accident Most accidents resulted in one death.

Rare events had 2 or more deaths, visible in both lollipop and bar plots.

How Many Times Did Tesla Drivers Die? Tesla driver fatalities were observed in a significant proportion of cases.

Breakdown by year/model/country shows the US and certain models (e.g., Model S, Model 3) dominate.

Proportion of Events Where Occupants Died Roughly 47% of events involved at least one Tesla occupant or driver death.

Distribution of Events Hitting Cyclists/Pedestrians A minority (~10-20%) of events involved hitting cyclists or pedestrians.

Most events involved only vehicle occupants.

Events With Occupant/Driver Death + Cyclist/Pedestrian Death Very rare (usually <3%): accidents where both a Tesla occupant/driver and a cyclist/pedestrian died.

Frequency of Collisions With Other Vehicles Majority of events involved a Tesla colliding with another vehicle.

Pie and bar plots confirm this as the dominant scenario.

c. Event Distribution Across Models¶

Model S and Model 3 are the most commonly involved in fatal events, followed by Model X and Model Y.

A significant fraction of records had the model unspecified (-).

d. Distribution of Verified Tesla Autopilot Deaths Very few events had verified Tesla Autopilot deaths (per dataset).

The overwhelming majority had zero verified autopilot fatalities.

Summary¶

Analysis Point Key Inference
Data Cleaning Dataset cleaned, missing & irrelevant columns removed
Events by Date/State/Country US, especially California, is the hotspot; increase over time
Deaths per Accident Most events: 1 death; multi-death rare
Tesla Driver Fatalities Notable fraction; most frequent in US and Model S/3
Occupant Deaths Proportion ~47% of events include Tesla occupant/driver death
Cyclist/Pedestrian Events Minority of cases; rare to have both occupant & cyclist/pedestrian death
Collisions With Other Vehicles Majority of accidents involve another vehicle
Model Distribution S and 3 are most common models in fatal accidents
Verified Autopilot Deaths Exceptionally rare

Overall Conclusion¶

Most fatal Tesla accidents are in the US, especially California, with single deaths being the norm.

Collisions with other vehicles are far more frequent than with cyclists/pedestrians.

The Model S and Model 3 are the most often involved models.

Verified autopilot-related deaths are extremely rare in this dataset.

Almost half of the fatal events involved at least one Tesla occupant/driver death.
